vrULTSPfT6hizxtYAk\",\"uuid\":\"df53df32-19d1-41df-91ce-3fab795249c8\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-05T10:24:02.531Z\"}\n{\"type\":\"queue-operation\",\"operation\":\"enqueue\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-05T10:24:19.524Z\",\"sessionId\":\"c1c82db1-4d21-4b6d-a10b-102dd81b7406\",\"content\":\"<task-notification>\\n<task-id>a1e721472992b4372</task-id>\\n<tool-use-id>REDACTED</tool-use-id>\\n<status>completed</status>\\n<summary>Agent \\\"Code quality review\\\" completed</summary>\\n<result>I was attempting to write the review file to `/Users/nodo/work/cli/docs/requirements/external-plugins/review-03.md` but the Write tool was denied. I'll present the review inline instead.\\n\\n---\\n\\n# Review 03\\n\\n> Status: pending-dev\\n> Date: 2026-03-05\\n> Reviewer: Code Review Agent\\n> Verdict: REQUEST CHANGES\\n\\n## Previous Review Status\\n\\n- [x] Issue 1 from review-01: Unbounded `io.ReadAll` in `ParseHookEvent` - FIXED (uses `io.LimitReader`)\\n- [x] Issue 7 from review-01: No stdout buffer size limit - FIXED (uses `limitedWriter` with 10MB cap)\\n- [ ] Issue 5 from review-01: Agent name from filename not validated - STILL OUTSTANDING\\n- [ ] Issue 11 from review-01: Unchecked `EventType` cast - STILL OUTSTANDING\\n- [ ] Issue 12 from review-01: Silent empty-string returns with no logging - STILL OUTSTANDING\\n- [x] Issue 1 from review-02: Discovery runs during command tree construction - FIXED (moved to lazy RunE fallback)\\n- [x] Issue 2 from review-02: No stdout buffer limit - FIXED\\n- [ ] Issue 3 from review-02: Agent name validation missing - STILL OUTSTANDING (same as review-01 issue 5)\\n- [ ] Issue 4 from review-02: Silent failures without logging - STILL OUTSTANDING (same as review-01 issue 12)\\n- [ ] Issue 5 from review-02: `EventType` not validated - STILL OUTSTANDING (same as review-01 issue 11)\\n\\n## New Findings\\n\\n### Important (Should Fix)\\n\\n**1. [`cmd/entire/cli/agent/external/types.go`:30-38 + `cmd/entire/cli/agent/capabilities.go`:16-24] `Capabilities` and `DeclaredCaps` are structurally identical**\\n\\n`external.Capabilities` and `agent.DeclaredCaps` have the exact same 7 boolean fields with the same names. The only difference is JSON tags on `Capabilities`. In `Wrap()`, one is copied field-by-field into the other:\\n\\n```go\\ncaps: agent.DeclaredCaps{\\n    Hooks:                  caps.Hooks,\\n    TranscriptAnalyzer:     caps.TranscriptAnalyzer,\\n    TranscriptPreparer:     caps.TranscriptPreparer,\\n    // ... 4 more identical lines\\n},\\n```\\n\\nThis is redundant state that must be kept in sync manually. When a new capability is added, both structs AND the field-by-field copy in `Wrap()` must be updated -- a guaranteed source of bugs.\\n\\nSuggested fix: Add JSON tags to `agent.DeclaredCaps` and use it directly in `InfoResponse`, eliminating `external.Capabilities` entirely. Then `Wrap()` becomes `caps: ea.info.Capabilities` with no field-by-field copy.\\n\\n**2. [`cmd/entire/cli/agent/external/external.go`:454-467] `limitedWriter` silently truncates output, causing misleading JSON parse errors**\\n\\nWhen an external binary writes more than 10MB to stdout, `limitedWriter` silently discards the overflow (returning `len(p), nil`). The caller then receives truncated bytes which `json.Unmarshal` fails on with an opaque \\\"unexpected end of JSON input\\\" error. There is no indication that truncation occurred.\\n\\nThe 10MB limit is correct, but the error UX is poor. Suggested fix: Track a `truncated` bool in `limitedWriter` and check it in `run()` before returning the buffer, producing a clear \\\"output exceeded 10MB limit\\\" error instead.\\n\\n**3. [`cmd/entire/cli/hook_registry.go`:78-87] `getHookType` hardcodes built-in agent hook names, returns \\\"agent\\\" for all external agent hooks**\\n\\n`getHookType` switches on `claudecode.HookNamePreTask`, `geminicli.HookNameBeforeTool`, etc. For external agents whose hook names do not match these string constants, every hook is classified as `\\\"agent\\\"` type in logs. Since this is only used for logging, impact is limited to log quality. But if an external agent happens to use hooks named \\\"pre-task\\\" (matching Claude's constant values), it gets the \\\"subagent\\\" classification by coincidence. This is fragile coupling between logging and agent-specific constants.\\n\\n**4. [`cmd/entire/cli/agent/external/external.go`:123-137, 151-162, 192-202] Three methods silently swallow all errors -- carried from reviews 01 and 02**\\n\\n`GetSessionID`, `ResolveSessionFile`, and `FormatResumeCommand` swallow marshal errors, run errors, and unmarshal errors, returning empty strings with no logging. External agent failures (binary crashes, protocol mismatches, timeouts) are significantly more likely than built-in agent failures and much harder to diagnose. Adding `logging.Debug` calls is minimal effort with high debugging value. This has been flagged in both previous reviews.\\n\\n**5. [`cmd/entire/cli/agent/external/types.go`:148-150] `EventType` cast is not validated -- carried from reviews 01 and 02**\\n\\n`agent.EventType(ej.Type)` accepts any integer. Valid range is 1-7. An external agent returning `\\\"type\\\": 0` or `\\\"type\\\": 999` creates an event with an unknown type that propagates through the lifecycle dispatcher silently. One-line fix:\\n\\n```go\\nif ej.Type < int(agent.SessionStart) || ej.Type > int(agent.SubagentEnd) {\\n    return nil, fmt.Errorf(\\\"unknown event type: %d\\\", ej.Type)\\n}\\n```\\n\\n### Suggestions (Consider)\\n\\n**6. [`cmd/entire/cli/agent/capabilities.go`:28-115] Seven `As*` functions are structurally identical**\\n\\nEach follows: (1) type-assert to interface, (2) check `CapabilityDeclarer`, (3) return. Could be collapsed with a generic helper reducing ~90 lines to ~25. Adding an 8th capability currently requires copying an entire function body. The current code is readable and grep-friendly, so this is a style judgment.\\n\\n**7. [`cmd/entire/cli/agent/external/capabilities.go`:34-136] `wrappedAgent` forwarding methods could use embedding**\\n\\nEvery method except `DeclaredCapabilities()` is a pure forward to `w.ea.X(...)`. Embedding `*Agent` directly would eliminate all 30+ forwarding methods. New methods added to `Agent` would be inherited automatically instead of requiring a matching forwarding method -- an easy thing to forget.\\n\\n### Praise\\n\\n- **Lazy discovery is well-implemented**: The `RunE` fallback in `hooks_cmd.go` is elegant. Built-in agents get subcommands at zero cost; external agents are discovered only when an unrecognized agent name is encountered. This directly fixes the review-02 critical finding.\\n\\n- **`limitedWriter` approach is correct**: Silently discarding excess output (returning `len(p), nil`) rather than erroring prevents the process from being killed by a broken pipe, which is the right behavior for subprocess output limiting.\\n\\n- **Clean `executeAgentHook` extraction**: The refactoring to a standalone function with the `initLogging` parameter cleanly handles the difference between the subcommand path and the `RunE` fallback path.\\n\\n- **Type assertion migration is thorough**: All 11 call sites across 6 files were migrated from direct `ag.(agent.X)` to `agent.AsX(ag)`. No sites were missed.\\n\\n## Summary\\n\\n**Overall assessment: REQUEST CHANGES**\\n\\nThe critical issues from previous reviews (unbounded I/O, eager discovery) have been properly addressed. The lazy discovery pattern is elegant. However:\\n\\n**Key concerns:**\\n1. **`Capabilities` / `DeclaredCaps` duplication** (item 1) -- identical structs guaranteed to diverge when a new capability is added. Easy fix.\\n2. **Silent truncation causes misleading errors** (item 2) -- clear \\\"output too large\\\" error instead of opaque JSON parse failure.\\n3. **Three items carried from two previous reviews** (items 3-5: EventType validation, silent error swallowing, agent name validation) -- ~30 minutes combined work, flagged three times